Craving a Turkish breakfast for so long and found Turkitch basis many reviews online. We reached at 10 am, found street parking easily it being a weekend. We ordered the Turkish breakfast (for 2) and pistachio baklava. The entire order and meal readiness took about 20 minutes. We initially thought we would get to go boxes to dine in(which is what most businesses do in COVID these days- which is so not fun when dining in) but we were pleasantly surprised to see a platter with cheese, dips, salami and salad and another platter with borek (bread) , Sucuklu Yumurta (a la shakshuka) and sujuk eggs with meatball side. Now I don’t know where to begin. The cheese with the variety of dips (7 to be precise) was heaven on earth. The authentic chocolate, strawberry marmalade, honey, sesame dips and more were just divine. We kept sighing with every bite! The show stopper is borek! The warmest, gooiest, tastiest bread we ever ate - rolled in cheese and spices! The sucuklu yumurta was a flavorful combo of eggs and veggies and blended well with the borek. Meatballs - no words - half poached eggs and delicious oil was worth every penny! The turkish tea- oh! I don’t know where to start!!! The turkish tea blew us away and baklawa - we were transported to Turkey - like now! All in all- highly recommend, worth the price, the location and the lazy brunch weekend! My spouse is so NOT a brunch person and he promises this will be his go to spot. Thank YOU turkitch team!

Absolute worst service. I have never been treated so rudely at a restaurant in Chicago- and I eat out pretty frequently. This was our first time going to Turkitch and I was so excited that I invited our family friends to come with us to enjoy our Sunday brunch together. Well, first of all, this is not a place for families- maybe for friends. Yes, they do have a high chair for babies, but they, so rudely, answer your question when you ask for one. The tables are so small- not even enough to accommodate a family of 3, let alone a group. We ordered Turkish menemen and soudjuk omelet. Well, they did not even bring bread with either until I went to the counter and asked for it (should have been natural).. Since we were a group we also got soudjuk and cheese simit, a few baked goods and burek, none of which were fresh (simit was better relative to the others- but way below expectations). When I went to get a PAID refill for the tea thermos we had, the male employee treated me in the most disrespectful manner until I told him that I had my wallet with me to pay! (It is not like I was going to runaway with the tea thermos!!) The only employee that I was happy with was the girl who refilled my thermos- she was very kind and deserves all kinds of promotions. When I complained to her about how rudely I was treated (not expecting anything to change; just told her that I regretted coming there for a Sunday brunch), she told the other employee who brought us a plate of cookies and apologized, hence the 2 stars.  I must also mention that it was not busy at all; I could have understood the behavior (although still can’t be justified) had the restaurant been full. Never going back.
